 <fr:p>The inverse to the <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KI.xml"
addr="jms-00KI"
title="Closure of functions under identity and composition">identity function</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {id}_{A}\colon  A\to  A]]></fr:tex> is simply itself.</fr:p>
 <fr:p>Fix <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijections</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon  B\to  C]]></fr:tex>, so that we have <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">inverses</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}\colon  B\to  A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g^{-1}\colon  C\to  B]]></fr:tex>. The <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">inverse</fr:link> to the <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KI.xml"
addr="jms-00KI"
title="Closure of functions under identity and composition">composite function</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\circ  f\colon  A \to  C]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KI.xml"
addr="jms-00KI"
title="Closure of functions under identity and composition">composite</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}\circ  g^{-1}\colon  C \to  A]]></fr:tex>. The <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KS.xml"
addr="jms-00KS"
title="Section-retraction pair">section/retraction</fr:link> conditions follow by those for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> using the <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00IP.xml"
addr="jms-00IP"
title="Associativity and unit laws of relational composition">associative and unit laws of composition</fr:link>.</fr:p>
